genous issues and best practices, and several of its chapters review efforts to increase supports for families in need. Contributions from new and international authors illustrate the endemic nature of child welfare challenges and how we can learn from these experiences. Contributors provide recommendations for promoting best practice and enhancing resilience among children and families. Closing chapters within each section and at the end of the book summarize key theoretical and practice issues along with recommendations to improve the research, policy, and practice continuum in child welfare. The challenge is to translate good research into policy and practice in ways that enhance the life chances of children who need our care and protection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild welfarexCanada. 0aChild welfarexResearchxCanadaxCanada. 0aChild welfarexResearchzCanada. 0aChild welfarezCanada. 4aLaw: Child Advocacy. 4aPolitical Science: Social Policy. 4aSocial Science: Child Studies. 4aSocial Science: Social Work. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAnglin, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBadry, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBala, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaudry, Madeleine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackstock, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrousseau, Michèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallahan, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela